things we need to do to take

00:28:05.910 --> 00:28:11.340
that call to action
moving forward?

00:28:11.340 --> 00:28:12.890
&gt;&gt; David J. Bailey: You know,

00:28:12.890 --> 00:28:15.160
I think [inaudible
speaker] great question.

00:28:15.160 --> 00:28:16.460
I wish I had all the answers.

00:28:16.460 --> 00:28:21.060
I think that the, there's been
a tremendous amount of work

00:28:21.060 --> 00:28:23.720
over the past ten years,
and it's accelerated

00:28:23.720 --> 00:28:25.220
over the past five years.

00:28:25.220 --> 00:28:30.360
You know, we now have a
national agenda around literacy.

00:28:30.360 --> 00:28:39.070
Because there is a much more
dedicated approach to using data

00:28:39.070 --> 00:28:41.940
in order to make decisions,
it gets people on board.

00:28:41.940 --> 00:28:44.760
It gets people from both
political parties on board.

00:28:44.760 --> 00:28:48.030
And the mayors of the nation
have actually been driving this

00:28:48.030 --> 00:28:49.580
I think more than anyone else.

00:28:49.580 --> 00:28:53.870
It really falls to
the local communities.

00:28:53.870 --> 00:28:56.270
But when I think about
it, what can we do more?

00:28:56.270 --> 00:29:00.880
And I think that, you know, you
have these two great efforts --

00:29:00.880 --> 00:29:05.870
health care, which consumes
three trillion dollars a year,

00:29:05.870 --> 00:29:08.690
and you have the
education budget,

00:29:08.690 --> 00:29:11.190
and you have this
giant literacy effort.

00:29:11.190 --> 00:29:17.040
In some ways, they're kind of in
silos, and, you know, certainly,

00:29:17.040 --> 00:29:23.760
the literacy data and the
health data have both landed

00:29:23.760 --> 00:29:27.200
on the social determinants
of health, that that is

00:29:27.200 --> 00:29:29.960
where we can make a difference.

00:29:29.960 --> 00:29:34.040
And I think even greater
emphasis on attempting

00:29:34.040 --> 00:29:38.310
to intervene early in
that first 1000 days.

00:29:38.310 --> 00:29:41.030
I think that is the
critical learning period

00:29:41.030 --> 00:29:45.820
at which developmental pathways
can be positively altered,

00:29:45.820 --> 00:29:50.120
and it requires far less
money and effort to do that.

00:29:50.120 --> 00:29:51.720
So what does that mean?

00:29:51.720 --> 00:29:54.270
I think we need to start
on the OB side, actually.

00:29:54.270 --> 00:29:56.500
I think that with prenatal
visits, mothers need

00:29:56.500 --> 00:30:00.370
to be informed how
critical reading, talking,

00:30:00.370 --> 00:30:05.040
and singing are to
their newborn baby.

00:30:05.040 --> 00:30:09.010
I don't know if to the fetus is
where we need to go, but maybe.

00:30:09.010 --> 00:30:12.050
But beyond that, you know,

00:30:12.050 --> 00:30:21.230
having literacy be a primary
point on which medical,

00:30:21.230 --> 00:30:22.530
the entire medical team --

00:30:22.530 --> 00:30:27.240
OB, pediatrics, family
practice -- gets on board.

00:30:27.240 --> 00:30:28.540
You know, the American Academy

00:30:28.540 --> 00:30:31.820
of Pediatrics has a
fabulous policy statement

00:30:31.820 --> 00:30:34.120
and developed fabulous
materials.

00:30:34.120 --> 00:30:39.740
A minority of pediatricians
actually do it.

00:30:39.740 --> 00:30:42.840
And the reasons are
many, you know --

00:30:42.840 --> 00:30:46.470
time, potentially reimbursement.

00:30:46.470 --> 00:30:49.730
Other factors include
not knowing,

00:30:49.730 --> 00:30:51.720
not being comfortable
with the tools.

00:30:51.720 --> 00:30:53.900
Are the tools really validated?

00:30:53.900 --> 00:30:58.120
And not being comfortable about,
are there folks in the community

00:30:58.120 --> 00:31:02.750
who are, who can truly intervene
once we've identified potential

00:31:02.750 --> 00:31:04.700
reading vulnerabilities?

00:31:04.700 --> 00:31:06.720
I think the new tool kit
that the AAP has come

00:31:06.720 --> 00:31:08.780
up with helps them
with that if, you know,

00:31:08.780 --> 00:31:12.300
once it gets massively
distributed.

00:31:12.300 --> 00:31:17.070
So I believe alignment,
not just within silos,

00:31:17.070 --> 00:31:18.650
because I think the
literacy world seems

00:31:18.650 --> 00:31:22.660
to be pretty well aligned,
but aligning the effort

00:31:22.660 --> 00:31:27.020
with health care, with
policy, with education,

00:31:27.020 --> 00:31:30.780
then I think we can
really make a difference.

00:31:30.780 --> 00:31:34.450
For instance, with education,
it is very difficult to break

00:31:34.450 --> 00:31:39.000
into the school system,
for someone in health care

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:42.300
to run a study longitudinally
over several grades

00:31:42.300 --> 00:31:43.600
to understand

00:31:43.600 --> 00:31:46.790
if an intervention's really
having a long-term effect.

00:31:46.790 --> 00:31:49.900
And I think that if we can
find ways to break those silos

00:31:49.900 --> 00:31:56.490
such that the large, different
pieces can then come together,

00:31:56.490 --> 00:32:00.310
I think we'll make
much faster progress.

00:32:00.310 --> 00:32:04.070
I think there's, you know,
in effect, there's a lot

00:32:04.070 --> 00:32:05.680
of money out there, you know.

00:32:05.680 --> 00:32:09.250
There's probably 30 to 40% of
health care is probably wasted.

00:32:09.250 --> 00:32:14.700
You know, if we can reduce that
waste and apply it to this type

00:32:14.700 --> 00:32:19.030
of effort into education,
I think over the long haul,

00:32:19.030 --> 00:32:23.370
you'll see a healthier
population.

00:32:23.370 --> 00:32:26.550
The problem is the will
to do it, you know.

00:32:26.550 --> 00:32:29.850
It's difficult to make that
type of massive change.

00:32:29.850 --> 00:32:32.810
But if we could just
gain some alignment

00:32:32.810 --> 00:32:36.090
between all the different,
large constituencies,

00:32:36.090 --> 00:32:38.500
I think we'd make
bigger progress.

